      <h1>Varroa monitoring schedule</h1>
      <p class="lede">Season-by-season thresholds and simple methods to spot Varroa early and act in good time.</p>

      <div class="grid cols-3">
        <section class="card" id="why-monitor">
          <h2>Why monitor?</h2>
          <p>Varroa destructor weakens colonies by feeding on developing bees and spreading viruses. Regular, light-touch checks let you time any interventions well and avoid unnecessary treatments.</p>
          <ul class="list">
            <li>Use one consistent method for comparable results.</li>
            <li>Record counts with date, weather, brood status.</li>
            <li>Respond to trends, not one-off spikes.</li>
          </ul>
        </section>

        <section class="card" id="methods">
          <h2>Common methods</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Alcohol wash</strong> (300 bees): accurate; counts mites per 100 bees.</li>
            <li><strong>Powdered sugar roll</strong> (300 bees): non-lethal alternative; slightly less accurate.</li>
            <li><strong>Sticky board/natural drop</strong>: board under an open mesh floor for 3 days; lower precision but useful trend line.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="muted">Pick one as your primary method and sanity-check with another occasionally.</p>
        </section>

        <section class="card" id="quick-thresholds">
          <h2>Quick thresholds</h2>
          <ul class="list">
            <li><strong>Alcohol/sugar roll:</strong> ~<em>2â€“3 mites/100 bees</em> in spring warrants closer watch; <em>â‰¥3â€“4</em> in the main season usually triggers action.</li>
            <li><strong>Natural drop (3-day):</strong> persistent daily averages above low single digits outside broodless periods suggest rising pressure.</li>
          </ul>
          <p class="muted">Use local best practiceâ€”thresholds vary by climate, season, and colony strength.</p>
        </section>
      </div>

      <div class="divider"></div>

      <section id="schedule">
        <h2>Season-by-season schedule (UK-leaning, adapt locally)</h2>

        <h3 id="late-winter">Late winter / very early spring</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Quick natural-drop check (3 days) during a steady cold spell.</li>
          <li>If broodless confirmed, note this windowâ€”itâ€™s when many beekeepers apply winter treatments.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="spring">Spring build-up (Marchâ€“May)</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Monthly <strong>alcohol/sugar roll</strong> on ~300 bees from the brood nest.</li>
          <li>Track trend. If counts reach ~2â€“3/100 bees, plan a follow-up check within 2 weeks.</li>
          <li>Rotate drone comb only if you already use it for managementâ€”donâ€™t add complexity if new.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="summer">Earlyâ€“mid summer (Juneâ€“July)</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Every 2â€“3 weeks: roll test + spot natural-drop trend.</li>
          <li>Approaching <em>â‰¥3â€“4/100 bees</em> or fast upward trend â†’ prepare an intervention once honey is off.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="late-summer">Late summer after harvest (Julyâ€“August)</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Re-test within a week of taking supers off; treat promptly if over threshold.</li>
          <li>Re-check efficacy 10â€“14 days after treatment (same method).</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="autumn">Autumn (Septemberâ€“October)</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Monthly check to confirm downward trend post-treatment.</li>
          <li>Ensure colonies enter winter with low mite loads.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3 id="winter">Winter (Novemberâ€“January)</h3>
        <ul class="list">
          <li>Look for broodless windows for a single accurate natural-drop or targeted check.</li>
          <li>Only minimal disturbance; prioritise hive weather-tightness and stores.</li>
        </ul>

        <p class="notice">Health note: choose approved interventions for your country and follow the label. This page focuses on <em>monitoring</em>; treatment specifics vary by region and product.</p>
      </section>

      <section id="how-to">
        <h2>Method snapshots</h2>

        <h3 id="alcohol-wash">Alcohol wash (most accurate)</h3>
        <ol class="list">
          <li>Collect ~300 bees (about half a cup) from a brood frame into a ventilated jar.</li>
          <li>Add alcohol, shake gently 60 seconds, pour through mesh onto a white tray to count mites.</li>
          <li>Calculate mites per 100 bees; record and compare over time.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3 id="sugar-roll">Powdered sugar roll (non-lethal)</h3>
        <ol class="list">
          <li>Collect ~300 bees into a jar with mesh lid.</li>
          <li>Add 2 tbsp icing sugar, roll to coat, wait 1 minute, shake over white tray; count mites.</li>
          <li>Release bees back to the hive.</li>
        </ol>

        <h3 id="sticky-board">Natural drop / sticky board</h3>
        <ol class="list">
          <li>Insert sticky board under open mesh floor for 72 hours.</li>
          <li>Count daily average; repeat monthly to track trend.</li>
        </ol>
      </section>

